node.text:
Here’s the recipe for the keto vanilla birthday cake I made with Ube cream cheese frosting! This was a fun experiment. I was genuinely surprised by how moist and fluffy the cake came out! BTW, definitely also had “real” cake...and milkshakes...and bread pudding too cuz...there’s no holding back on your birthday!!!

Cake ingredients: 

3 c almond flour
1 c coconut flour
4 tsp baking powder
1/2 tsp salt
1.5 c vegan butter, softened
1.5 c monkfruit sugar
8 eggs
1 c almond milk
2 tsp vanilla extract

Ube cream cheese frosting ingredients:

1 c monkfruit powdered sugar
16 oz vegan cream cheese, softened
1/2 c softened vegan butter
1/2 tsp of ube extract

Method:

1. Mix all cake ingredients together
2. Bake for 45 min - 1 hr depending on your oven, until firm on top, at 350 F
3. Once firm, remove from oven, let cool, then slice into 2 or 3 layers
4. For frosting, whip all ingredients together, then chill in fridge
5. Once both the cake and frosting are cool, add frosting between each layer of cake, and then on the outside
6. Slice and enjoy!

Makes 16 servings!

Recipe adapted from @thebigmansworld keto birthday cake.

I wanted to see once and for all what simple 2-3 ingredient healthy cookie recipe would taste the best! So, I put 5 recipes against each other!

1.5 banana + 1/2 c coconut flour

1 banana + 1/2 c rolled oats

1.5 banana + 1/2 c pea protein

1 banana + 1/2 c dessicated coconut

1 banana + 1/2 c dessicated coconut + 1/2 c peanut powder

Watch the video to find which recipe failed and which recipe won! I’m always looking for an easy staple healthy cookie recipe...which do you wanna try?

I love dancing! It is my favorite form of cardio because it never feels like cardio, you know what I mean?! I'm sad that I can't take dance classes or fitness classes right now, but it's all good because we need to do our part to flatten the curve! And that means social distancing!
.
Anyway, my friend @thefitnessmarshall tagged me in the Your Turn Dance Challenge and I was like nooooo SO MUCH CHOREO TO LEARN but once I got started it wasn't that bad. Thank you Caleb for the lil push :) I had a lot of fun getting my groove on, so if you guys wanna learn it too, just follow my tutorial! I tacked on the last 4 counts and YES IT INCLUDES A HAIR WHIP YOU ARE VERY WELCOME.
.
Here's how this all got started BTW!
.
1️⃣Started by @daniellenatoni - this challenge is designed to see how much choreography we can build by each person adding 4 counts at a time!
2️⃣Danielle then threw it to @officialtaniabaron who did her 4 counts who then threw it to @shaunt who threw it to @drlaurenfitz who thew it to @thefitnessmarshall who has now thrown it to me!
3️⃣I added on my own 4 counts inspired by my heels classes and NOW I CHALLENGE MY LIL SISTER @jackelynho to add the next 4 counts!
4️⃣Who will be next and how long will this keep going?!?😍🙌🏼🤷🏼‍♀️
#yourturndancechallenge #dance #dancechallenge #socialdistancing

node.text:
Been holding this back from you. 

When Blogilates first launched at @target Jan 2021, I had only one shot to prove myself. I was given 4 months to show that my stuff could sell. If sales were weak, you’d never see Blogilates at Target again.

I had already poured my entire soul into each design, and it was now up to the customers to decide. First, is a gold weight anything ANYONE even wanted? Secondly, would a picture of an Asian woman with black hair and small eyes turn people off? Honestly and sadly, I thought so. That’s why I fought against having my picture on the packaging.

Growing up as the child of immigrants, I had to learn to assimilate. My parents told me to never tell anyone at school that we spoke a 2nd language at home in fear that they’d assume I was a foreigner, kick me out of English, and put me in ESL. I ended up feeling ashamed to speak Vietnamese at all, so I stopped, even at home, and the sad reality is, I can barely communicate with my grandparents now.

I actually didn’t unpack all of this until I dug deep to figure out why I didn’t want to show my face on my own products. The dark truth: I still had resentment towards my heritage and didn’t want it to hold me back. Plus I had heard that there was a concern about the performance of Blogilates in less diverse regions like the South…

Launch day comes. I’m nervous. I keep telling myself, “if it’s meant to be it will be.” I’ve designed products I 100% stand behind and truly believe in. And if the market doesn’t like it, or like me, or whatever, at least I failed giving it every bit of my soul.

And then…

It was like the line was never in stores.

BECAUSE BLOGILATES SOLD OUT.

IN A MATTER OF A FEW WEEKS.

Not only did the collection outperform all projections…

IT SOLD THE BEST IN THE SOUTH 😅

Next thing I knew, I received the call from the buyer. “Start designing” he said. “We need Blogilates back in stores ASAP.”

So I’m here to officially announce that beginning Sept 19 my newest collection will be at all Targets! I can’t believe 😭 Swipe to the end for a sneakpeek.

Finally, thank you. None of this would even be remotely possible without your love. I’m am forever grateful.

♥️Cassey

node.text:
Wasn’t cool enough for the after party so Sam and I went to In N Out instead.

AND IT WAS 👌

The red carpet experience yesterday was super special and definitely a dream come true…but in actuality, I felt super out of place. It wasn’t my world but I’m so grateful to be exposed to it! Maybe one day I’ll feel more comfortable if I ever get the chance to do that again.

Omg also! All I could think of when we were at In N Out was @iskra’s iconic black dress on the cashier counter photo they she took from a few years ago! I wasn’t as brave to DO THAT exactly but we did manage to find a quiet corner to shoot this 🙃 Eating fast food after a glam event in my glam dress is kind of a tradition. Did it after prom, after the wedding, and now, after my first red carpet. I love the irony and juxtaposition of it all. 

Okay I’ve got nothing else meaningful to say so that’s all.

♥️Cassey

node.text:
And here she is. My first ever red carpet dress design.

!!!

LIFE IS SO CRAZY SOMETIMES.

My ultimate life goal as a little girl was to design gowns for famous actresses to walk the red carpet. I was addicted to magazine recaps of award show fashion, obsessing over anything romantic, sparkly or flowy with daring slits, backless exits and unconventional  necklines. Never did I think or honestly, even remotely desire to be the first one to wear my own creation on the carpet.

I mean it was just a week ago that I got the invite from @tiktok to represent @tiktokcreators at the @marvel world premiere of @shangchi, then I sketched my dream gown and prayed that @designerdaddy_ could help me make it, then he somehow miraculously made it in 3 days and overnighted it to me on day 4 so that tonight, I could walk my first ever Hollywood red carpet in the gown of my dreams! 😭

It was SUCH an honor to be at the premiere of our generation’s first Asian superhero movie. I experienced a roller coaster of emotions today, moved not only by the poetically complicated story of family, but also by the beauty of how my culture was being represented. That’s why when I got the invite to walk to carpet, I knew I had to design a gown that paid homage to traditional Asian clothing, but with a modern twist. As a proud Chinese Vietnamese American raised by immigrant parents, I wanted both of my cultures to have an influence on my dress tonight. I intentionally placed a mandarin collar (Chinese qipao) at the nape of my neck and waist high slits (Vietnamese ao dai) up both sides of my gown.

Oh! And @samlivits was SO WORRIED about my lace cutouts. We did an at-home run through this past weekend when I thought I could just go commando and then after a side turn we both quickly realized that underwear was absolutely 1000% necessary 😅

Anyway, that’s a wrap on this dress! You should also def go see this movie when it comes out. It’s really REALLY good. Congrats @simuliu!!!

♥️Cassey

Omg. I just learned how to make 30 sec almond milk and I AM FLOORED.

Not only is it cheaper than the store bought kind, but it tastes better and the best part - it only has 2 ingredients. You can alter how milky, fatty or sweet you want it too!

INGREDIENTS

🥜1-2 TBS of any nut butter (try to use one that is made of just nuts and salt)
💧4 C water

Then blend. That’s it! If you like it sweeter, which I do, add some monk fruit sugar to taste. Drink what you need then save the rest in the fridge! Not sure how long it saves just yet (literally just learned this for the first time yesterday from TikTok via @lilsipper) and I DEFINITELY will be doing this going forward! I am so happy!!!

What’s your fave non-milk milk?

♥️Cassey

I’m gonna be super real with you about my body and you’re not gonna like it.

When it comes to what I want to look like versus what I’m willing to do to get there, it’s a choice. Some people can do nothing and eat whatever and still be lean. Other people can do everything and eat nothing and still be overweight.

Me? I’m neither, but I lean towards the latter. In fact, my 23andMe report literally says I have genes that predispose me to be overweight. I compared my results to my other family members’ and for some reason, I’m the only one with that predisposition. I always had a hard time with my weight growing up, so I kinda felt something was up, but seeing the test results gave me 2 very clear choices: 

1️⃣ blame it on genes, say it’s not fair, and move on

or

2️⃣ accept the information, accept it’s not fair, and do something about it.

Throughout my 20s, I wallowed in choice number one, working out and eating clean and being upset that I was working so much harder than other people and not seeing the results I wanted.

Then, 2 years ago, I made a choice. I embarked on a personal journey that also included intentional weight loss. And no, for the record, I didn’t hate my body because contrary to popular belief, you are allowed to change yourself and still love yourself. For those of you who were around for my #90dayjourney, you know how intense that whole period was in my life.

Anyway, since then I’ve been able to maintain my weight loss and I have to be super honest with you - it’s not effortless. At all.

Do I still work out like how I did on my 90 Day Journey? Yes.

Do I still eat like how I ate on my 90 Day Journey? Yes. (But dessert once in a while ofc!)

Is it worth it? Yes. 100%. For me.

Knowing how hard I have to work to achieve my current body has actually empowered me. Because the TRUTH empowers me. I’m grateful that, for me at least, it’s a choice I CAN make.

I grind daily with my career and in workouts so it’s a lifestyle that suits me for the moment. Maybe it’s just how I’m built but I actually find joy in being challenged. So until other conditions in my life change, this is how it is and I’ve come to accept it and fully embrace it.

♥️Cassey

node.text:
Growing up I always wished I was taller. I also wished I had bigger eyes. Bigger boobs. Wished I was skinnier. Prettier. Cooler. Smarter.

Now I wish I had not wasted so much time worrying about being “perfect” through eyes that were not my own.

It’s easy to say - but times were so different then. Those who went to middle school and high school in the early 2000s, don’t you feel like it was all about blending in? Like, being different was weird. And these days I feel like the MORE DIFFERENT you are, the COOLER you are!

Anyway, back to the first wish. 

Getting taller! It’s actually a little in your control! Many of us have some hidden inches in us that we need to unleash! All you have to do is work on your posture (probably not the best if you’ve got a desk job and are glued to your phone all day) and you can increase your height a bit! Up to 2 inches in some people’s cases. And you know what - if you want more, you can wear heels 👠 and put your hair in a high bun, but after that I can’t help you anymore. 

Just try this stretch for starters! It feels great. Plus it’ll increase flexibility in your back and your shoulders! 

Just a minute a day! Have fun!

♥️Cassey 

PS: I’m wearing The Vivid Crop Bra and Sculpt Pocket Biker Short in Marine Marble from @popflex_active

Nope. That’s not 🧀.

It’s @housefoodsamerica TOFU! And it looks (and tastes, in my opinion) deceivingly close to the real deal. PLUS to my fellow lactose intolerant friends, tofu is a great way to get the protein without the dairy! You have to try my recipe for these cute little caprese bites (one of my fave Italian treats) that are quick and easy to make!

Ingredients:

◻️1 pack firm tofu from @housefoodsamerica #ad
◻️Cherry tomatoes, halved
◻️Basil leaves
◻️Balsamic glaze
◻️Salt & pepper to taste

Method:

1️⃣ Drain and press tofu, 10 min
2️⃣ Cut tofu into cubes
3️⃣ Sprinkle tofu with salt & pepper
4️⃣ On a toothpick, place 1 cherry tomato half, 1 tofu cube, 1 basil leaf, and other half cherry tomato.
5️⃣ Then drizzle with balsamic glaze. 

And I am going to pat myself on the back because @samlivits ALSO liked this recipe.

Would you try this?

♥️Cassey

Interesting how there’s so much prejudice when it comes to weight. And I’m not even talking about hundreds of pounds. Just twenty.

These are real comments I received. It’s pretty striking to see how members of different communities view the same exact thing. My body. 

[Side note: I’m going to use the terms “fat” and “skinny” going forward in this post to define me 20 lbs heavier versus now for simplicity of writing.]

FAT IN A BIKINI
1️⃣“You’re so inspirational and so brave!”
2️⃣ “Why don’t you have abs??”

SKINNY IN A BIKINI
1️⃣“I liked you better before…”
2️⃣ “Too thin.”

FAT WHILE TEACHING WORKOUTS
1️⃣“I like seeing a normal body do these workouts.”
2️⃣ “If you cared about your career, you’d lose weight.”

SKINNY WHILE TEACHING WORKOUTS
1️⃣“You have an eating disorder.”
2️⃣ “She doesn’t even workout. She’s just skinny.”

And to sum it all up…

BEFORE 90 DAY JOURNEY:
“You’re a bad role model for all women!!! Hypocrite! UNFOLLOW.”

AFTER 90 DAY JOURNEY:
“How did you do it?”

I’m not going up call out the specific communities (and genders) making these remarks about my body and my intentions, but it was very much coming from members of groups with views so strong, it made them narrow minded. And you know what? That is so dangerous. Because it cuts you off from solution oriented thinking and in general, having empathy for other people’s individual backgrounds and journeys. It breeds ignorance too.

The point is: focus on yourself and your journey. Look at what other people did for inspiration and for guidance, but don’t compare! And finally, it goes without saying, but saying it anyway, think about what you write.

We weren’t talking about mental health several years ago the way we are doing now, and I’m just so grateful I’m still here. So many of my fellow creators have burned out and left due to a myriad of personal reasons, but they all shared the burden of battling hateful comments and letting that affect their self worth. The truth is, my skin and heart have both thickened over the years in order to still be here. It’s not easy, but it’s ok. I’m ok.

Anyway, thank you for still being here with me. Your support helps me believe in myself everyday.

♥️Cassey
